# Security

## Site scoping

The application is multi-tenant. Every site-scoped resource MUST be accessed through `current_site` (or an association rooted on it).

- Good: `current_site.budget_lines.find(id)`
- Bad: `BudgetLine.find(id)`

When creating records, set `site_id` programmatically — never accept it from user input. The same applies to `admin_id` and `user_id` for ownership.

## Authentication

- `ApplicationController` applies `authenticate_user_in_site` as a global `before_action`. Inheriting from it gives you authentication for free.
- Admin-side controllers extend `GobiertoAdmin::AdminController`, which adds admin-session checks on top.
- A new public-facing controller that should require login must inherit from a base class that authenticates, or add the `authenticate_user_in_site` filter explicitly.

## Authorization

- Policies live in `app/policies/gobierto_admin/` and extend `GobiertoAdmin::BasePolicy`.
- A policy is initialized with `attributes: { current_admin:, current_site: }`.
- Use `policy.can_manage_module?(:module_name)` to gate admin-side module access. Use `policy.can_manage_site?(site)` for site-level checks. Use `policy.manage?` for the "is this a manager?" override.
- A new admin-side controller that touches a protected resource needs a policy check before destructive or sensitive actions.

## Strong parameters

- Define a private `permitted_params` helper on every controller that creates or updates records. Never pass `params` directly to `.create` / `.update`.
- Never permit ownership or scoping fields from user input: `site_id`, `admin_id`, `user_id`.
- Sensitive parameters are filtered from logs via `config/initializers/filter_parameter_logging.rb`. When adding a new sensitive field, add it to that filter list.

## Input sanitization

- HTML coming from users must be sanitized before storage with `rails-html-sanitizer` (already loaded). Don't trust client-side sanitization.
- For full-text search input, rely on `pg_search`'s built-in sanitization — don't interpolate user values into raw SQL.

## SQL

- Use ActiveRecord scopes and parameterized queries. When raw SQL is unavoidable, use `sanitize_sql` and `connection.quote`.
- Never interpolate user input into a SQL string.

## CSRF

- Maintain `protect_from_forgery with: :exception` in `ApplicationController` and any controller that accepts cookie-authenticated POSTs. Don't disable CSRF for convenience.

## Logs and monitoring

- Don't log full email addresses or other PII. Truncate or hash before logging.
- Do not commit secrets, tokens, or API keys. Use environment variables and Ansible-managed secrets.

## Captcha

- Public-facing forms (consultations, contact, signups) should use `invisible_captcha` to deter bots. Follow the existing pattern in similar forms.
